    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "wait i'm confused. i thought basal was meant to maintain my levels throughout the night, not for meals? if i skip it because i didnt eat much, wont that actually make things worse if my body still needs that background insulin to stay stable? i'm worried about the crash if i take it, but i'm also worried about being too high. what do u mean by a correction dose for that?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Basal insulin is for background maintenance, but if you've barely eaten, your body is going to run low, so skipping it is a gamble. A correction dose is a quick, short-acting insulin shot, like a rapid-acting bolus, to immediately bring down any high readings or prevent a dangerous low. If you're unsure, take a small correction dose now, perhaps 1 unit, and then monitor closely. You'll see how your body reacts to that immediate adjustment.",
      "source": "target",
